Plain — Syntax
Nerijus Ramanauskas <nerijus@signaintermedia.com>


KEYWORD

    Any sequence of bytes that is not a reserved character.
    Reserved characters (see Library/Source/Framework/Host/Version.c):

        ` " ' [ { ] } , ; : space tab CR LF

    The literals "yes", "no", and "none" are reserved keyword values.


WHITESPACE

    Space (0x20), horizontal tab (0x09), line feed (0x0A), carriage
    return (0x0D).

    Whitespace is allowed anywhere between tokens.


COMMENT

    Starts with a grave accent ` (0x60), ends at end of line.

        x = 42    ` this is a comment


STATEMENT (NODE)

    A node is a keyword optionally followed by arguments:

        keyword arg1 arg2 arg3 ...

    When evaluated, the keyword is looked up in the frame; the bound
    procedure or function is invoked with the resolved arguments.
    Arguments are separated by whitespace or commas (both are equivalent).

        print "hello", "world"
        print "hello" "world"


EXPRESSION (NODE)

    A statement wrapped in [...] whose result is used as a value:

        [add 1, 2]
        [x + 3]

    Expressions can be nested freely.


INFIX EXPRESSION

    A special two-argument expression form using an operator symbol
    as the first argument:

        [name op value]

    The left operand must be a named variable (a keyword), not a literal.
    Operator symbols: +  -  *  /  %  =  !=  <  >  <=  >=  and  or

    When used as a top-level statement with =, it means assignment:

        x = 42
        name = "Plain"

    When used inside [...], = means equality comparison:

        [x = 42]    ` yes or no


BLOCK (LIST)

    A deferred sequence of statements enclosed in { }:

        { print "hello"; print "world" }

    Blocks are not evaluated until explicitly needed (by if, repeat,
    procedure bodies, etc.).

    Colon shorthand — opens a block inline, closed by the next semicolon:

        if condition: print "yes" ;


PROGRAM (LIST)

    A sequence of statements separated by semicolons:

        a = 1; b = 2; print [add a, b]

    The last statement does not require a semicolon.
    Newlines are whitespace — statements on separate lines still need
    semicolons if there are multiple per logical unit.


LITERALS

    Boolean       yes   no
    Nil           none
    Integer       42   -7   (C style)
    Real          3.14   1.5e10   (C style)
    String        "hello"   'it\'s fine'   (backslash escapes)
    Keyword       used for variable references (see Semantics)
    Node          [keyword args]   used for expressions
    Block         { statements }   used for deferred bodies
